label.value: transferase activity, transferring acyl groups, acyl groups converted into alkyl on transfer

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of an acyl group from one compound (donor) to another (acceptor), with the acyl group being converted into alkyl on transfer.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a transition metal ions -  a transition metal is an element whose atom has an incomplete d-subshell of extranuclear electrons, or which gives rise to a cation or cations with an incomplete d-subshell. Transition metals often have more than one valency state. Biologically relevant transition metals include vanadium, manganese, iron, copper, cobalt, nickel, molybdenum and silver.

label.value: transition metal ion transmembrane transporter activity

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of transition metal ions from one side of a membrane to the other. A transition metal is an element whose atom has an incomplete d-subshell of extranuclear electrons, or which gives rise to a cation or cations with an incomplete d-subshell. Transition metals often have more than one valency state. Biologically relevant transition metals include vanadium, manganese, iron, copper, cobalt, nickel, molybdenum and silver.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + 3-dephospho-CoA -eq- 2'-(5''-triphosphoribosyl)-3'-dephospho-CoA + adenine.
Catalysis of the transfer of a pyruvyl (oxopropanoyl) group from one compound to another.

Catalysis of the transfer of an L-fucosyl group from GDP-beta-L-fucose to an acceptor molecule to form an alpha-(1--gt-6) linkage.
Catalysis of the transfer of an alpha-L-fucosyl residue from GDP- beta-L-fucose to the serine hydroxy group of a protein acceptor.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with an endoplasmic reticulum (ER) retention sequence, a specific peptide sequence that ensures a protein is retained within the ER.
Any small opening in a membrane that allows the passage of gases and|or liquids.

label.value: sodium-transporting ATP synthase activity, rotational mechanism

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  ADP + phosphate + Na+(out) -eq- ATP + H2O + Na+(in), by a rotational mechanism.

label.value: proton-transporting ATP synthase activity, rotational mechanism

definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of protons from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  ADP + H2O + phosphate + H+(in) -eq- ATP + H+(out), by a rotational mechanism.
Catalysis of the reaction -  1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 4,5-bisphosphate + ATP -eq- a 1-phosphatidyl-1D-myo-inositol 3,4,5-trisphosphate + ADP + 2 H(+).
Modulates the activity of the enzyme 1-phosphatidylinositol-3-kinase activity.
Catalysis of the reaction -  deoxyadenosine + H2O -eq- deoxyinosine + NH3.
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-azetidine-2-carboxylic acid + acetyl-CoA -eq- CoA-SH + N-acetyl azetidine-2-carboxylic acid.
Catalysis of the transfer of carboxylic acids from one side of the membrane to the other. Carboxylic acids are organic acids containing one or more carboxyl (COOH) groups or anions (COO-).
Catalysis of the transfer of protons from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  ATP + H2O + H+(in) -eq- ADP + phosphate + H+(out), by a rotational mechanism.
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  ATP + H2O + Na+(in) -eq- ADP + phosphate + Na+(out), by a rotational mechanism.
Catalysis of the transfer of 3'-phosphoadenosine 5'-phosphosulfate, a naturally occurring mixed anhydride synthesized from adenosine 5'-phosphosulfate, from one side of a membrane to the other.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a retinoid X receptor.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a thyroid hormone receptor.

Catalysis of the reaction -  histone H3 N6-acetyl-L-lysine (position 9) + H2O -eq- histone H3 L-lysine (position 9) + acetate. This reaction requires the presence of NAD, and represents the removal of an acetyl group from lysine at position 9 of the histone H3 protein.

Catalysis of the reaction -  histone H4 N6-acetyl-L-lysine (position 16) + H2O -eq- histone H4 L-lysine (position 16) + acetate. This reaction requires the presence of NAD, and represents the removal of an acetyl group from lysine at position 16 of the histone H4 protein.

Catalysis of the reaction -  acetyl-CoA + histone H4 L-lysine (position 16) -eq- CoA + histone H4 N6-acetyl-L-lysine (position 16). This reaction represents the addition of an acetyl group to the lysine at position 16 of histone H4.

Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + histone H3 L-lysine (position 9) -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + histone H3 N6-methyl-L-lysine (position 9). This reaction is the addition of a methyl group onto lysine at position 9 of the histone H3 protein.

Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + histone H3 L-lysine (position 36) -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + histone H3 N6-methyl-L-lysine (position 36). This reaction is the addition of a methyl group onto lysine at position 36 of the histone H3 protein.

Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + histone H3 L-lysine (position 27) -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + histone H3 N6-methyl-L-lysine (position 27). This reaction is the addition of a methyl group onto lysine at position 27 of the histone H3 protein.

Catalysis of the transfer, in a beta 1,3 linkage, of D-glucuronic acid (GlcUA) from UDP-D-glucuronic acid to N-acetyllactosamine (galactosyl beta-1,4-N-acetylglucosamine).
Catalysis of the transfer, in a beta 1,3 linkage, of D-glucuronic acid (GlcUA) from UDP-GlcUA to asioloorosomucoid.

Catalysis of the transfer, in a beta 1,3 linkage, of D-glucuronic acid (GlcUA) from UDP-GlcUA to the disaccharide galactosyl beta-1,3 N-acetylgalactosamine, a common component of glycoproteins and glycolipids.
Catalysis of the reaction -  acetyl-CoA + an N-hydroxyarylamine -eq- CoA + an N-acetoxyarylamine.

label.value: oxidoreductase activity, acting on X-H and Y-H to form an X-Y bond

definition.value: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which X-H and Y-H form X-Y.

label.value: oxidoreductase activity, acting on X-H and Y-H to form an X-Y bond, with oxygen as acceptor

definition.value: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which X-H and Y-H form X-Y and the acceptor is oxygen.

label.value: oxidoreductase activity, acting on hydrogen as donor, with a quinone or similar compound as acceptor

definition.value: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which hydrogen acts as an electron donor and reduces quinone or similar compound.

label.value: oxidoreductase activity, acting on hydrogen as donor, with other known acceptors

definition.value: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which hydrogen reduces a known acceptor other than a cytochrome, an iron-sulfur protein, NAD, NADP, or a quinone or similar compound.

label.value: oxidoreductase activity, acting on paired donors, with incorporation or reduction of molecular oxygen, with NAD(P)H as one donor, and the other dehydrogenated

definition.value: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which hydrogen or electrons are transferred from NADH or NADPH and one other donor, and the latter donor is dehydrogenated.

label.value: oxidoreductase activity, acting on the CH-NH group of donors, flavin as acceptor

definition.value: Catalysis of an oxidation-reduction (redox) reaction in which a CH-NH group acts as a hydrogen or electron donor and reduces a flavin.

Catalysis of the reaction -  L-arabinitol + NAD(+) -eq- L-ribulose + H(+) + NADH.
Catalysis of the reaction -  dTDP-6-deoxy-L-talose + NADP(+) -eq- dTDP-4-dehydro-6-deoxy-L-mannose + H(+) + NADPH.
